# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grpc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grpc/core-concepts] An introduction to key gRPC concepts, with an overview of gRPC architecture and RPC life cycle.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] For language-specific details, see the quick start, tutorial, and reference documentation for your language of choice.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Like many RPC systems, gRPC is based around the idea of defining a service, specifying the methods that can be called remotely with their parameters and return types.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] By default, gRPC uses protocol buffers as the Interface Definition Language (IDL) for describing both the service interface and the structure of the payload messages.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] It is possible to use other alternatives if desired.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] You’ll learn more about the different types of RPC in the RPC life cycle section below.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Starting from a service definition in a `.proto` file, gRPC provides protocol buffer compiler plugins that generate client- and server-side code. gRPC users typically call these APIs on the client side and implement the corresponding API on the server side.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Synchronous RPC calls that block until a response arrives from the server are the closest approximation to the abstraction of a procedure call that RPC aspires to.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] On the other hand, networks are inherently asynchronous and in many scenarios it’s useful to be able to start RPCs without blocking the current thread.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The gRPC programming API in most languages comes in both synchronous and asynchronous flavors.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] You can find out more in each language’s tutorial and reference documentation (complete reference docs are coming soon).
[src:grpc/core-concepts] In this section, you’ll take a closer look at what happens when a gRPC client calls a gRPC server method.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] For complete implementation details, see the language-specific pages.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] First consider the simplest type of RPC where the client sends a single request and gets back a single response.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The server can then either send back its own initial metadata (which must be sent before any response) straight away, or wait for the client’s request message.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Which happens first, is application-specific.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Once the server has the client’s request message, it does whatever work is necessary to create and populate a response.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The response is then returned (if successful) to the client together with status details (status code and optional status message) and optional trailing metadata.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] If the response status is OK, then the client gets the response, which completes the call on the client side.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] A server-streaming RPC is similar to a unary RPC, except that the server returns a stream of messages in response to a client’s request.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] After sending all its messages, the server’s status details (status code and optional status message) and optional trailing metadata are sent to the client.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] This completes processing on the server side.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The client completes once it has all the server’s messages.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] A client-streaming RPC is similar to a unary RPC, except that the client sends a stream of messages to the server instead of a single message.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The server responds with a single message (along with its status details and optional trailing metadata), typically but not necessarily after it has received all the client’s messages.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] In a bidirectional streaming RPC, the call is initiated by the client invoking the method and the server receiving the client metadata, method name, and deadline.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] The server can choose to send back its initial metadata or wait for the client to start streaming messages.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Client- and server-side stream processing is application specific.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Since the two streams are independent, the client and server can read and write messages in any order.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] For example, a server can wait until it has received all of a client’s messages before writing its messages, or the server and client can play “ping-pong” – the server gets a request, then sends back a response, then the client sends another request based on the response, and so on.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] gRPC allows clients to specify how long they are willing to wait for an RPC to complete before the RPC is terminated with a `DEADLINE_EXCEEDED` error.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] On the server side, the server can query to see if a particular RPC has timed out, or how much time is left to complete the RPC.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Specifying a deadline or timeout is language specific: some language APIs work in terms of timeouts (durations of time), and some language APIs work in terms of a deadline (a fixed point in time) and may or may not have a default deadline.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] In gRPC, both the client and server make independent and local determinations of the success of the call, and their conclusions may not match.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] This means that, for example, you could have an RPC that finishes successfully on the server side (“I have sent all my responses!”) but fails on the client side (“The responses arrived after my deadline!”).
[src:grpc/core-concepts] It’s also possible for a server to decide to complete before a client has sent all its requests.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Either the client or the server can cancel an RPC at any time.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] A cancellation terminates the RPC immediately so that no further work is done.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Changes made before a cancellation are not rolled back.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Metadata is information about a particular RPC call (such as authentication details) in the form of a list of key-value pairs, where the keys are strings and the values are typically strings, but can be binary data.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Keys are case insensitive and consist of ASCII letters, digits, and special characters `-`, `_`, `.` and must not start with `grpc-` (which is reserved for gRPC itself).
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Binary-valued keys end in `-bin` while ASCII-valued keys do not.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] User-defined metadata is not used by gRPC, which allows the client to provide information associated with the call to the server and vice versa.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Access to metadata is language dependent.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] A gRPC channel provides a connection to a gRPC server on a specified host and port.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Clients can specify channel arguments to modify gRPC’s default behavior, such as switching message compression on or off.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] A channel has state, including `connected` and `idle`.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] How gRPC deals with closing a channel is language dependent.
[src:grpc/core-concepts] Some languages also permit querying channel state.
[src:grpc/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:grpc/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:grpc/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:grpc/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:grpc/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:grpc/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:grpc/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:grpc/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:grpc/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:grpc/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:grpc/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:grpc/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:grpc/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:grpc/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:grpc/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:grpc/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:grpc/introduction] An introduction to gRPC and protocol buffers.
[src:grpc/introduction] This page introduces you to gRPC and protocol buffers. gRPC can use protocol buffers as both its Interface Definition Language (**IDL**) and as its underlying message interchange format.
[src:grpc/introduction] If you’re new to gRPC and/or protocol buffers, read this!
[src:grpc/introduction] If you just want to dive in and see gRPC in action first, select a language and try its **Quick start**.
[src:grpc/introduction] In gRPC, a client application can directly call a method on a server application on a different machine as if it were a local object, making it easier for you to create distributed applications and services.
[src:grpc/introduction] As in many RPC systems, gRPC is based around the idea of defining a service, specifying the methods that can be called remotely with their parameters and return types.
[src:grpc/introduction] On the server side, the server implements this interface and runs a gRPC server to handle client calls.
[src:grpc/introduction] On the client side, the client has a stub (referred to as just a client in some languages) that provides the same methods as the server.
[src:grpc/introduction] gRPC clients and servers can run and talk to each other in a variety of environments - from servers inside Google to your own desktop - and can be written in any of gRPC’s supported languages.
[src:grpc/introduction] So, for example, you can easily create a gRPC server in Java with clients in Go, Python, or Ruby.
[src:grpc/introduction] In addition, the latest Google APIs will have gRPC versions of their interfaces, letting you easily build Google functionality into your applications.
[src:grpc/introduction] By default, gRPC uses Protocol Buffers, Google’s mature open source mechanism for serializing structured data (although it can be used with other data formats such as JSON).
[src:grpc/introduction] If you’re already familiar with protocol buffers, feel free to skip ahead to the next section.
[src:grpc/introduction] The first step when working with protocol buffers is to define the structure for the data you want to serialize in a *proto file*: this is an ordinary text file with a `.proto` extension.
[src:grpc/introduction] Protocol buffer data is structured as *messages*, where each message is a small logical record of information containing a series of name-value pairs called *fields*.
[src:grpc/introduction] Then, once you’ve specified your data structures, you use the protocol buffer compiler `protoc` to generate data access classes in your preferred language(s) from your proto definition.
[src:grpc/introduction] These provide simple accessors for each field, like `name()` and `set_name()`, as well as methods to serialize/parse the whole structure to/from raw bytes.
[src:grpc/introduction] So, for instance, if your chosen language is C++, running the compiler on the example above will generate a class called `Person`.
[src:grpc/introduction] You can then use this class in your application to populate, serialize, and retrieve `Person` protocol buffer messages.
[src:grpc/introduction] gRPC uses `protoc` with a special gRPC plugin to generate code from your proto file: you get generated gRPC client and server code, as well as the regular protocol buffer code for populating, serializing, and retrieving your message types.
[src:grpc/introduction] To learn more about protocol buffers, including how to install `protoc` with the gRPC plugin in your chosen language, see the protocol buffers documentation.
[src:grpc/introduction] While protocol buffers have been available to open source users for some time, most examples from this site use protocol buffers version 3 (proto3), which has a slightly simplified syntax, some useful new features, and supports more languages.
[src:grpc/introduction] Proto3 is currently available in Java, C++, Dart, Python, Objective-C, C#, a lite-runtime (Android Java), Ruby, and JavaScript from the protocol buffers GitHub repo, as well as a Go language generator from the golang/protobuf official package, with more languages in development.
[src:grpc/introduction] You can find out more in the proto3 language guide and the reference documentation available for each language.
[src:grpc/introduction] The reference documentation also includes a formal specification for the `.proto` file format.
[src:grpc/introduction] In general, while you can use proto2 (the current default protocol buffers version), we recommend that you use proto3 with gRPC as it lets you use the full range of gRPC-supported languages, as well as avoiding compatibility issues with proto2 clients talking to proto3 servers and vice versa.
